      • next

        public final boolean next​(long pageId)
                   throws IOException
        Description copied from class: PageCursor
        Moves the cursor to the page specified by the given pageId, if any, and returns true when it is ready to be processed. Returns false if for instance, the cursor was requested with PF_NO_GROW and the page most recently processed was the last page in the file.

        NOTE: When using read locks, read operations can be inconsistent and may return completely random data. The data returned from a read-locked page cursor should not be interpreted until after PageCursor.shouldRetry() has returned false. Not interpreting the data also implies that you cannot throw exceptions from data validation errors until after PageCursor.shouldRetry() has told you that your read was consistent.

        Specified by:
        next in class PageCursor
        Throws:
        IOException

      • isPotentiallyReadingDirtyData

        private boolean isPotentiallyReadingDirtyData​(long lastClosedTransactionId)
        When reading potentially dirty data in case if our page last modification version is higher than requested lastClosedTransactionId; or for this page file we already evict some page with version that is higher than requested lastClosedTransactionId. In this case we can't be sure that the data of the current page is satisfying the visibility requirements, and we pessimistically will assume that we are reading dirty data.
        Parameters:
        lastClosedTransactionId - last closed transaction id
        Returns:
        true in case if we reading potentially dirty data for requested lastClosedTransactionId.

      • openLinkedCursor

        public PageCursor openLinkedCursor​(long pageId)
        Description copied from class: PageCursor
        Open a new page cursor with the same pf_flags as this cursor, as if calling the PagedFile.io(long, int, org.neo4j.io.pagecache.tracing.cursor.PageCursorTracer) on the relevant paged file. This cursor will then also delegate to the linked cursor when checking PageCursor.shouldRetry() and PageCursor.checkAndClearBoundsFlag().

        Opening a linked cursor on a cursor that already has a linked cursor, will close the older linked cursor. Closing a cursor also closes any linked cursor.

        Specified by:
        openLinkedCursor in class PageCursor
        Parameters:
        pageId - The page id that the linked cursor will be placed at after its first call to PageCursor.next().
        Returns:
        A cursor that is linked with this cursor.

      • getBoundedPointer

        private long getBoundedPointer​(int offset,
                               int size)
        Compute a pointer that guarantees (assuming size is less than or equal to pageSize) that the page access will be within the bounds of the page. This might mean that the pointer won't point to where one might naively expect, but will instead be truncated to point within the page. In this case, an overflow has happened and the outOfBounds flag will be raised.

      • nextBoundedPointer

        private long nextBoundedPointer​(int size)
        Compute a pointer that guarantees (assuming size is less than or equal to pageSize) that the page access will be within the bounds of the page. This works just like getBoundedPointer(int, int), except in terms of the current offset. This version is faster when applicable, because it can ignore the page underflow case.

      • copyTo

        public int copyTo​(int sourceOffset,
                  PageCursor targetCursor,
                  int targetOffset,
                  int lengthInBytes)
        Description copied from class: PageCursor
        Copy the specified number of bytes from the given offset of this page, to the given offset of the target page.

        If the length reaches beyond the end of either cursor, then only as many bytes as are available in this cursor, or can fit in the target cursor, are actually copied.

        Note that copyTo is only guaranteed to work when both target and source cursor are from the same page cache implementation. Using wrappers, delegates or mixing cursor implementations may produce unspecified errors.

        Specified by:
        copyTo in class PageCursor
        Parameters:
        sourceOffset - The offset into this page to copy from.
        targetCursor - The cursor the data will be copied to.
        targetOffset - The offset into the target cursor to copy to.
        lengthInBytes - The number of bytes to copy.
        Returns:
        The number of bytes actually copied.

      • shiftBytes

        public void shiftBytes​(int sourceStart,
                       int length,
                       int shift)
        Description copied from class: PageCursor
        Shift the specified number of bytes starting from given offset the specified number of bytes to the left or right. The area left behind after the shift is not padded and thus is left with garbage.

        Out of bounds flag is raised if either start or end of either source range or target range fall outside end of this cursor or if length is negative.

        Specified by:
        shiftBytes in class PageCursor
        Parameters:
        sourceStart - The offset into this page to start moving from.
        length - The number of bytes to move.
        shift - How many steps, in terms of number of bytes, to shift. Can be both positive and negative.
